<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Workers Strike To Protest Union Leader's Arrest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1802045194 Paris AFP in Spanish 0318 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1802045194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 17 Feb (AFP) -- Five thousand 
Colombian oil industry workers stopped working this Thursday to 
protest the arrest of a union leader accused of subversive 
activities. The intended duration of the action is unknown. 
  Following the orders of a prosecutor who linked Freddy 
Pulecio, a member of the board of directors of the Workers Trade 
Union (USO), to a case of alleged rebellion, Colombian secret 
agents arrested Pulecio in eastern Arauca during the past hours. 
USO is comprised of Ecopetrol [Colombian Petroleum Enterprise] 
workers. 
  The strike has negatively affected the north-central 
Barrancabermeja installations, which houses the country's most 
important oil refinery, and has forced Ecopetrol to implement 
contingency measures to maintain the production rate and fuel 
distribution. 
  The strike started on Thursday afternoon and it is not known 
if it will last 24 hours or if it will be extended indefinitely. 

</TEXT>

