<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reina Denies Anti-Castro Force Training on Swan Islands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1702160694 Tegucigalpa Voz de Honduras Network in Spanish 
1145 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1702160694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa Voz de Honduras Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "The Morning Paper" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpt] President Carlos Roberto Reina traveled to the 
Swan Islands yesterday to investigate certain strange rumors 
that troops planning to overthrow Fidel Castro were on the 
island and to confirm that only authorized aircraft, boats, and 
other vessels are allowed to transit Honduran airspace and 
waters. 
  [Begin recording] [Reina] One reason for my visit to the 
Swan Islands was to investigate complaints that there might be 
some sort of strange activity going on there related in some way 
to the Caribbean situation. I have gone all over the islands 
and seen what I just told you. Let this serve as evidence to 
deny any suspicions, rumors, or comments that differ from the 
truth. 
  [Unidentified reporter] What strange activities were 
reportedly going on there? 
  [Reina] We were advised by a nearby country that some sort 
of 
armed action against a Caribbean country was being prepared 
there. 
  [Reporter] What country? 
  [Reina] When you speak of the Caribbean, the political 
problem has always been Cuba, the Republic of Cuba, which I hope 
will reenter the inter-American system when the island can meet 
the system's requirements. These complaints had been kept 
secret, but they could surface later and tarnish Honduras' 
image. We do not want our country to be hurt in any way. On 
the contrary, we want Honduran prestige to afford us all 
possible international assistance and worldwide acceptance, 
because democracy is reaffirmed every day in Honduras. [passage 
omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

