<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Communique Announces New Ministers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1702133694 Paris AFP in Spanish 1224 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1702133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Lima, 17 Feb (AFP) -- Peruvian President Alberto 
Fujimori accepted on Wednesday the resignation of Alberto 
Bustamante y Bustamante's, president of the Council of 
Ministers. The Presidential Press Secretariat announced that 
Bustamante would be replaced by Foreign Minister Efrain 
Goldenberg. 
  Bustamante, who had been appointed president of the Council 
of Ministers in August, tendered his resignation six days after 
the promulgation of a law that granted military courts 
jurisdiction over the "La Cantuta" case, an incident in which 
human rights were seriously violated and in which members of the 
Peruvian Armed Forces have been charged. 
  The Presidential Palace communique indicated that new Prime 
Minister Goldenberg will assume his post this Thursday while 
continuing to hold his post as foreign minister. 
  President Fujimori also accepted Education Minister Raul 
Victor Alfaro's resignation, who just two days ago denied any 
disagreement in the government regarding the La Cantuta case. 
The new education minister will be Jorge Reyes. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

