<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Closed-Door Talks Begin Early </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2102142694 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1328 
GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2102142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Luis Armenta from the "Panorama" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The dialogue for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas 
will begin earlier than originally planned. Although the talks 
between the 19 EZLN [Zapatist National Liberation Front] 
delegates headed by Subcommander Marcos and Commissioner Manuel 
Camacho Solis will formally begin today, some meetings were held 
yesterday. 
  According to reports released yesterday and early today, 
three groups were formed to define negotiation mechanisms. 
Although the reconciliation process formally begins at 0900 
[1500 GMT] today, the first phase of the meeting will be private 
and accredited reporters will not be allowed coverage. We do not 
expect to receive any information on the first direct meeting 
between the 19 EZLN delegates, among whom are four women, 
Commissioner Camacho Solis, and mediator Bishop Samuel Ruiz 
until midday. 
  The EZLN representatives have spent 18 hours inside the San 
Cristobal de Las Casas cathedral, which is now being called the 
cathedral of peace. Standing guard at the cathedral are unarmed 
military policemen, Red Cross volunteers, and members of 
nongovernment organizations. These three circles were 
established on Saturday, and they operate day and night with 
changes every four hours. Working in these circles are 
approximately 450 volunteers, a similar number of persons from 
nongovernment organizations, and approximately 500 soldiers. 

</TEXT>

