<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRD, Other Parties Form `United People' Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1902003294 Panama City Telemetro Television Network in 
Spanish 1730 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1902003294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Telemetro Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telemetro Reports" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The first political alliance was presented today 
before the Electoral Tribunal Secretariat. It is called the 
United People [Pueblo Unido], and it comprises the PRD 
[Democratic Revolutionary Party], the Labor Party, and the 
Liberal Republican Party. 
  According to Ernesto Perez Balladares, presidential 
candidate 
for the alliance, the purpose of this electoral merger is to 
present a program to resolve the country's most pressing 
problems. Perez Balladares also stressed that the possible 
reentry of the former military into politics would pose danger 
to the country. 
  [Begin recording] [Perez Balladares] I respect the right 
that 
members of the military or former members of the military have 
to participate in politics and party politics. Nevertheless, I 
must call attention to the fact that it is dangerous if they 
unite as a power bloc or somehow again become a determinant 
force. Even though this may only be the start of what could be 
the return of such a force, I must draw attention to it, because 
the desperation to attain power could lead someone to resort to 
something we all wish to forget and leave in the past. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Dr. Ernesto Perez Balladares, is the 
purge, so to speak, which evidently has been taking place within 
the PRD, designed to ensure that civilian forces lead the party? 
  [Perez Balladares] I believe we have instituted an internal 
democracy, which is very evident to the great majority of the 
Panamanian people. This internal democracy has caused 
individuals or people who disagree the party's main ideals to be 
cast aside by the very dynamics of democracy. I do not think we 
have had... [pauses] I do not like the term purge, but we have 
had a continual influx of internal democracy. This is also 
proof positive that we have pledged to maintain this internal 
democracy and to make it effective nationwide the day we come to 
power. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

