<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Group Formed To Investigate Illegal Armed Groups </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1902180594 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1501 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1902180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 19 Feb (DPA) -- The so-called "Joint 
Group for the Investigation of Illegal Armed Groups with 
Political Motivations" announced today the start of its 
operations at the national level as part of the process for the 
consolidation of peace in El Salvador. 
  The group, which will be responsible for investigating 
criminal activities committed by illegal armed groups with 
political motivations, better known as "death squads," announced 
in paid ads published in today's San Salvador newspapers that 
since 1 February its offices have been established and it has 
the necessary personnel to carry out its duties. 
  The previously mentioned organization was created by the 
Salvadoran Government with the consent of UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali given the increase in the number of "death 
squad-style" murders late last year, which even cost the lives 
of various commanders of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation 
Front (FMLN). 
  The joint group "invites all people and entities that may 
have any information or are willing to help discover illegal 
armed groups with political motivations to come forward so these 
groups can be eradicated from our country and prosecuted 
according to the law." 
  It also points out that the "confidentiality of information 
provided to the Joint Group for the Investigation of Illegal 
Armed Groups with Political Motivations is absolutely 
guaranteed." 
  The group will investigate all criminal actions attributed 
to 
illegal armed groups committed between 16 January 1992, the date 
on which the peace agreements were signed by the government of 
President Alfredo Cristiani and the FMLN, and March of the 
present year. 
  Among the members of the Joint Group are: Human Rights 
Ombudsman Carlos Molina; Diego Garcia Sayan, chief of the human 
rights division of the UN Observer Mission for El Salvador; and 
two Salvadoran Government representatives. 
  Last Thursday, while visiting El Salvador, Brian Atwood, 
special envoy of the U.S. State Department, said the U.S. 
Government has decided to provide technical and economic support 
to the Joint Group for the eradication of illegal armed groups 
with political motivations from El Salvador. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-33218 </DOCNO>
