<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2002035294 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2002035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Finance Minister Julio Sosa Rodriguez denied press 
reports stating that Carlos Hernandez had been appointed as the 
person who would be responsible for the Banco Latino 
intervention process. 
  [Begin Sosa recording] He was never a candidate. So far 
there are no candidates and that is something that must be 
determined by the president of the Republic. There are some 
persons who, considering the superintendent's resignation, could 
occupy the position. I believe that at this moment it would not 
be fitting for me to start speculating on names. As I said, 
that will be determined by the president after discussing it 
with the Senate of the Republic. [end recording] 
  The finance minister's statements were made after his five 
hour interpellation before the National Congress. He also 
referred to the resignation by Banco Latino's intervention board 
and stated that the creation of an administration board will not 
undermine the authority of those who are already involved. 
According to him, it is only a manner of expediting the entire 
process. In conclusion, he did not discard the possibility that 
Fogade's [Deposit Guarantee Fund] financial assistance to some 
banks could be eliminated. 
  [Begin Sosa recording] We would first have to determine what 
the situation is, because transient financial assistance which, 
let's say, does not increase, could help to stabilize a specific 
situation. However, I believe that financial assistance that is 
constantly on the rise will undoubtedly lead us to at least some 
type of intervention. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

