<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Soldiers Reported in Southern Areas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1802202194 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1925 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1802202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Santa Fe de Bogota, 18 Feb (DPA) -- It was 
learned today in Santa Fe de Bogota that residents of Tumaco, a 
port on the southern coast of Colombia, have charged that U.S. 
soldiers are allegedly conducting operations in that area. 
  The charges made to EL ESPECTADOR reporters in Narino 
Department, where Tumaco is located, state that soldiers, 
wearing uniforms with the acronym "USA" on them, have even been 
asking residents of the area for their identification papers. 
  According to several residents of that port town, the 
soldiers, who "are tall, well-built, and blond-haired" have 
conducted "sudden patrols" of the town, supposedly while 
conducting antidrug trafficking operations. 
  The alleged actions of the foreign soldiers adds yet another 
ingredient to the problem Colombia is facing because of the 
presence of some 150 U.S. soldiers in Juanchaco, a small town 
located along the Pacific coast but quite removed from Tumaco, 
where, according to official reports, they are building a school 
and health center. 
  The soldiers arrived in Colombia in early January and their 
arrival unleashed a heated debate that included the State 
Council asking congress to investigate President Cesar Gaviria 
for violating the country's sovereignty. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

