<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cundinamarca Violence Considered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2102202194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1739 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2102202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Cundinamarca Department has been among the hardest 
hit by the guerrillas, who have staged five attacks over the 
past few hours. This has prompted the authorities to increase 
security. 
  A special security council meeting is under way at this hour 
at the Cundinamarca governor's office. Presiding over the 
council are Governor Manuel Guillermo Infante, 13th Brigade 
Commander General Norberto Adrada, and Cundinamarca Police 
Commander Colonel Roberto Fajardo. 
  Departmental authorities are considering the serious public 
order problem which affected at least five towns in the 
department this weekend. The authorities are considering new 
strategies to counteract the guerrillas' actions and security 
measures to guarantee the electoral campaign. This weekend in 
Cundinamarca, the FARC [Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia] 
implemented a strategy aimed at isolating Bogota, which was 
drafted at the most recent guerrilla summit in La Uribe. The 
guerrillas operate on four fronts. In the south, they are 
located in the municipalities of Fusagasuga, Cabrera, Pasca, 
Gutierrez, Chipaque, and Fomeque. In the east, they are located 
in the municipalities of Ubala, Chacala, and the Chingaza area. 
In the northwest, they are located in Yacopi, Caparrapi, and 
Topaipi in La Palma and Villa Gomez on the Boyaca border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

