<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Valledupar Mayor Explains Guerrilla Checkpoint Events </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2102190394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1736 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2102190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A frustrated Valledupar Mayor Rodolfo Campos Soto 
told the National Newscast of how events unfolded at a guerrilla 
check point only 20 minutes away from his city. 
  [Begin recording] [Campos] We were returning from 
(?Mayapola) 
when, somewhere between Mayangola and Aguas Blancas, we 
discovered the guerrillas had set up a check point obstructing 
traffic. The guerrillas stopped every vehicle and encouraged 
support for a group called Caribbean Bloc composed of several 
FARC [Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia] fronts. They 
distributed a communique protesting the presence of U.S. troops 
in the country; they preached to the people who were there; and, 
after an hour and a half, allowed traffic to begin circulating 
again. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Were they aware of your presence, 
Mr. 
Mayor? 
  [Campos] No. My presence went totally unnoticed, which was 
also the case with the president of the Municipal Assembly, the 
president of the Municipal Council, Chamber of Representatives 
candidate Mauro Tapia, several councilmen, and virtually the 
entire municipal administration. The guerrillas were there 
simply to promote their new Caribbean Bloc. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

