<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement Signed With Canada To Build Biogenetic Lab </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1802210494 Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network in Spanish 
2200 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1802210494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] National Resources Minister Luis Alvarado announced 
that a biogenetic laboratory to study the lenga magallanica tree 
will be built in Tierra del Fuego Province. 
  This initiative falls within the framework of an agreement 
signed by the National Resources Ministry, Canadian Cooperation, 
and a private foundation interested in studying why this specie 
grows in an unfavorable environment. 
  The reason for this initiative is the intensive exploitation 
of this resource by wood mills that use the lenga tree to 
produce chips [preceding word in English]. 
  [Begin recording] [Alvarado] The idea is to carry out a 
scientific investigation that will tell us why this specie grows 
in such an unfavorable environment. What we want to do is build 
two sites on which this laboratory will be located. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Does this require a law? 
  [Alvarado] No. There is a direct agreement between the 
National Resources Ministry, Canadian Cooperation, and a private 
foundation. We estimate the research will take four to five 
years before the lenga tree can be grown in nurseries. [end 
recording] 
  If this initiative proves fruitful, Chile will be able to 
grow lenga forests and thus have a new resource to exploit, 
according to Alvarado, who is visiting the 12th Region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

