<F P=101> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Indifferent To U.S. Coca Interdiction Cutback </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1802195394 Cochabamba LOS TIEMPOS in Spanish 11 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PY1802195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cochabamba LOS TIEMPOS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] La Paz, 10 Feb (LOS TIEMPOS) -- Army General 
Staff senior officers said on 9 February in La Paz that the 
budget cutback in the drug-trafficking interdiction programs in 
the coca-producing countries announced by the U.S. Government 
"is immaterial to the Bolivian Armed Forces." 
  The military sources told LOS TIEMPOS that this attitude is 
to be understood to the extent that "the Army, the Navy, and the 
Air Force have never actually received these funds." 
  The military sources supported their opinions by pointing 
out 
that the U.S. Army spent more than $5 million in the name of 
Bolivia under the excuse of carrying out civic actions in the 
town of Santa Ana del Yacuma in Beni Department in 1992. 
  The sources noted: "In fact, barely $250,000 was invested in 
building a school that year." 
  In the opinion of our country's military authorities, the 
cutbacks in this year's interdiction programs announced by U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's administration "are a result of the 
U.S. Army's mismanagement of economic resources over the past 
few years." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

