<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Drug Trafficker Charges Regiment Manufactures Cocaine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1802200694 La Paz Television Nacional Network in Spanish 
1700 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1802200694 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Television Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] A drug trafficker's testimony is the cause of 
controversy in the political arena. The following is a report 
by Mario Espinoza, who will tell us about this and other issues 
such as the bid for the Cotapata-Santa Barbara road construction 
project and the government budget. 
  [Mario Espinoza] The testimony of drug trafficker Meco 
Dominguez, which was reported by the Fides news agency and 
carried by newspapers in La Paz and nationwide, has caused a 
true political earthquake. 
  The MIR [Movement of the Revolutionary Left] has come out to 
defend its party members and former President Paz Zamora by 
stating that [former Interior Minister] Guillermo Capobianco has 
called a news conference this morning in Santa Cruz and is 
willing to subject himself to any investigation. 
  At any rate, we are facing a unique situation because the 
drug trafficker has caused a political earthquake by slandering 
respectable institutions such as the Bank of Santa Cruz. 
  Moreover, MIR President Oscar Eid Franco has denied 
Dominguez' charges. [passage omitted] 
  [Unidentified anchorwoman] As was reported by Mario 
Espinoza, 
drug trafficker Meco Dominguez has made charges against the 
private banking industry and the Armed Forces. A Fides news 
agency report reads, text, that for the first time a Bolivian 
bank has been charged in alleged involvement in money laundering 
activities. 
  The report adds that the bank, which has connections with 
U.S. and Panamanian banks, obtained the funds from the Colombian 
and Bolivian drug cartels. 
  Moreover, according to what the controversial Meco Dominguez 
told fiscal and police officials, the Monchego regiment has 
become a cocaine manufacturing center. 
  Regarding the alleged money laundering activities conducted 
by the Bank of Santa Cruz, Meco Dominguez alleges he held a 
meeting with bank officials in 1990. He added that in 1989, 
through Juan Carlos Pereira Paz, bank transactions were 
conducted with this gentleman for the cashing of six checks for 
$50,000 each for the Cali cartel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

