<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian Protest Groups March Toward Mexico City </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2202182694 Paris AFP in Spanish 1516 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2202182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chilpancingo, Mexico, 22 Feb (AFP) -- About 700 
members of the 500 Years of Indian Resistance Council of 
Guerrero [Consejo Guerrerense 500 Anos de Resistencia Indigena] 
began a march to Mexico City to demand a solution to their 
claims and in support of the Zapatist National Liberation Army 
(EZLN). 
  The Indians, which make up the four ethnic groups that live 
in the 34 municipalities in Guerrero State, left Monday night 
with signs that read "Indians, never again second class 
citizens," "For a court that judges violations to Indian human 
rights," and "Solidarity with the noble and fair cause of our 
Chiapas brothers." Included in their requests, the demonstrators 
demand compliance with the EZLN demands for democracy, justice, 
and liberty; autonomy for the Indian peoples; the creation of a 
state fund for the development of their peoples; and that the 
state satisfy the needs of employment and services. 
  The Guerrero Indians and other Indians who have arrived from 
different parts of the country, on 3 March will participate in a 
Mexico City rally and they have requested an audience with 
Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari. 
  Yesterday the EZLN and the government began their first 
peace 
talks in San Cristobal de las Casas, in the southern State of 
Chiapas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

