<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Designated Ambassador to Cuba Rejects U.S. Blockade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2202152694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2034 GMT 21 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2202152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 21 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- Mexico will 
maintain its policy of asylum and respect for human rights of 
immigrants, but will not allow the use of its territory as a 
springboard for Cubans trying to go to the United States, a 
diplomatic source said today. 
  Carlos Alejandro Tello, the designated Mexican ambassador to 
Cuba, said Mexico "will maintain its policy rejecting the U.S. 
blockade against Cuba, implemented more than 30 years ago, and 
will advocate its elimination because it harms the Cuban people." 
  Asked if the Mexican Foreign Secretariat has asked its 
diplomats to report on the Chiapas situation in the countries 
where they are accredited, Tello said "we were instructed to 
tell the truth from the start of the incidents." He added that 
"if I am confirmed as ambassador to Cuba, I will do as I did in 
Moscow; I will say it is a local problem, a Mexican problem. 
There should be no foreign intervention and a political solution 
will be sought through dialogue." 
  He said he has received no special instructions for carrying 
out his duties in Cuba. "Mexico will not only maintain the 
excellent and solid relations that currently exist, but will 
strengthen them by redoubling efforts in the areas of tourism, 
oil, and industry," he stressed. 
  Tello, who has been the Mexican ambassador to Portugal and 
Russia, among other positions, expects to be confirmed 
ambassador to Cuba by a Congressional plenum on Wednesday [23 
February]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

