<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2202183594 </F>
<F P=103> PA2202183594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Nicaraguan economic developments monitored through 22 
February. 
  The Central Bank of Nicaragua announced that annual 
accumulated inflation reached 10.58 percent during the last 12 
months and that the cordoba had fallen 6.55 percent with respect 
to the U.S. dollar. According to the Central Bank, the 
aforementioned levels are in accordance with monetary adjustment 
policies applied by Violeta Chamorro's administration to control 
inflation, which reached 55,000 percent in 1990, the highest in 
the world. In January 1993, Nicaragua's economic authority 
decided to implement a 20.34-percent "macrodevaluation" of the 
cordoba and establish a 1 percent monthly fluctuation mechanism. 
(Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2105 GMT 15 Feb 94) 
  Oscar Aleman, director of the Foreign Trade department of 
the 
Economic and Development Ministry (MEDE), announced that 
Nicaragua had decided to stop granting licenses for the 
importation of Costa Rican dairy, canned, and grain products 
until that country decides to lift its import restrictions on 
similar items from Nicaragua. Aleman said the decision does not 
constitute a trade war but is a "tit for tat" situation because 
while Nicaragua allowed the unrestricted entry of Costa Rican 
goods, that country did the opposite. The foreign trade 
director added that before making the decision, the economy 
minister had contacted his Costa Rican counterpart and requested 
unrestricted passage for Nicaraguan goods. The Costa Rican 
minister explained that the call for restrictions was made by 
the private sector for reasons of competition. (Managua 
BARRICADA in Spanish 16 Feb 94 p 1, 8) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

