<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Confirms Past Employment of Ames' Wife </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2302020294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0057 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2302020294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 22 Feb (EFE) -- The Colombian 
Foreign Ministry today confirmed Maria del Rosario Casas Ames, a 
U.S. citizen of "Colombian origin" who the U.S. Government says 
is allegedly involved in espionage, worked for the Foreign 
Ministry between April 1982 and December 1983. 
  A Colombian Foreign Ministry press communique stated Mrs. 
Casas, "prior to her marriage, worked for the Foreign Ministry 
in the post of civilian attache 1 EX in the Colombian Embassy in 
Mexico." 
  It was reported in Washington today Casas worked as a "paid 
CIA agent in Mexico, where she worked as a cultural attache in a 
foreign embassy." The U.S. Justice Department announced on 21 
February the arrest of Casas and her husband, Aldrick Ames, a 
high-ranking CIA official, for allegedly spying for the 
dissolved Soviet Union and Russia. It is said they were "double 
agents," because they also "sold information" to the Russian KGB 
since 1985 for $1.5 million. 
  The Foreign Ministry added in the communique issued in Santa 
Fe de Bogota that "the Colombian Government is waiting for 
official confirmation about Mrs. Casas' alleged links to the 
U.S. CIA during the time when she worked as an official of the 
Colombian Embassy in Mexico." 

</TEXT>

