<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   * De Greiff Denies Disagreement Over Cali Cartel </TI></H3>
<H4>   * SEMANA Editor Responds </H4>
<F P=102> 94P20407B Santa Fe de Bogota SEMANA in Spanish 25 Jan 94 p 17 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20407B </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota SEMANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Response to Prosecutor General De Greiff's letter from the </F>
SEMANA editorial staff] 
  [Text] With regard to the first information, related to the 
differences between the national government and the Prosecutor 
General's Office regarding the surrender of persons linked to 
the Cali cartel, those differences are part of the public domain 
and have been reported by various communications media. In the 
recent past, even high-level government sources from the 
Prosecutor General's Office itself have described in detail to 
this magazine discrepancies of this sort with the government 
regarding the case of the Cali cartel. In addition, the week 
before last this disagreement was confirmed once again to SEMANA 
by a high-level source from President Gaviria's cabinet. With 
respect to the reports on differences between the Colombian 
Prosecutor General and his counterpart in the United States, 
these reports have been confirmed both by sources in the U.S. 
Government and by Colombian cabinet ministers. Thus, Mr. 
Prosecutor General, it is not a question of either inventions, 
or feverish imaginations, or irresponsible journalism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

