<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Spokesman Denies Franco To Resign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2202140694 Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network in 
Portuguese 2200 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2202140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Itamar Franco, who spent a week out of 
Brasilia, returned to his office in Planalto Palace but his stay 
in this capital will be short because he is scheduled to make 
four trips in the next 10 days. 
  Presidential spokesman Francisco Baker denied the president 
of the Republic is thinking of resigning to run for election. 
  Baker remarked that Franco cannot run for a seat in the 
Senate, as a Brasilia daily reported last weekend, because he is 
not affiliated with any political party. Moreover, the deadline 
to become affiliated expired in early January. 
  President Franco will only be at Planalto Palace a few days 
this week because on 24 February he will travel to Caxias do 
Sul, where on 25 February he will open the grape harvest. On 26 
February, he will travel to Porto Alegre, where he is scheduled 
to meet Rio Grande do Sul Governor Alceu Collares; from there he 
will go to Canoas, where he will dedicate the expansion of the 
(Aupec Pascualinho) refining plant. On 27 February, Franco will 
travel to Sao Jose dos Campos, Sao Paulo, to attend the 
launching of General Motors' economy model, (Costa). 
  Franco will return to Brasilia on 28 February after the 
launching ceremony, but he will only remain here a few days. 
  On 3 March, he is supposed to leave for Guaira, near 
Caracas, 
Venezuela to discuss issues related to border affairs, gold 
diggers, and the preservation of the environment. 

</TEXT>

