<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazilian Free Trade Zone Proposal Gets `Cold Reception' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2302190294 Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 
16 Feb 94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> PY2302190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Diplomats who attended the ALADI [Inter-American 
Integration Association] meeting of foreign ministers in 
Montevideo on 11 February told EL OBSERVADOR that the Brazilian 
proposal to establish a South American Free Trade Zone met with 
a cold reception. 
  The proposal was officially announced by Brazilian Foreign 
Minister Celso Amorim. It calls for the gradual lifting of 
customs tariffs in South American countries until a total 
liberalization of regional trade is achieved by 2005. 
  The same sources added that although the Brazilian proposal 
was not rejected, there was no enthusiasm for this new Latin 
American integration proposal in the short term. 
  The foreign ministers of Mercosur [Common Market of the 
South] countries will discuss this issue in their next meeting 
scheduled for March in Buenos Aires. They will also discuss the 
state of negotiations toward a common Mercosur customs tariff 
and the Brazilian proposal. 
  Uruguayan Foreign Minister Sergio Abreu did not comment on 
the issue but specified that the Brazilian proposal does not 
contradict Mercosur. 
  The foreign ministers attending the ALADI meeting avoided 
any 
specific comment on the eventual establishment of free trade 
zone in the short term. They reasserted their willingness to 
strengthen regional integration. 
  In a speech he delivered on 11 February at the ALADI 
meeting, 
the Argentine representative stressed the need to strengthen 
Latin American integration. He specified, however, that 
subregional organizations must first be enhanced. 
  If the Brazilian proposal is to be implemented on the same 
terms as those explained by Foreign Minister Amorim, 
negotiations should be undertaken this year so that the 10-year 
timetable for the elimination of custom tariffs may begin by 
1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

