<H3> <TI>   Concludes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2402010194 Havana Cuba Vision Network in Spanish 2320 GMT 
23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2402010194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Cuba Vision Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] After an official six-day visit to Cuba, Manuel 
Hermoso Rojas, the president of the government of the autonomous 
community of the Canary Islands, and his delegation departed 
today for Venezuela. At the Jose Marti International Airport, 
the Canarian delegation was greeted by Jose Ramon Fernandez, 
vice president of the Council of Ministers, and Vice Foreign 
Minister Isabel Allende Karem. Jose Antonio San Gil, Spanish 
ambassador to Cuba, and other Cuban personalities were also 
present at the ceremony. [passage omitted] 
  The last day of President Manuel Hermoso Rojas' official 
visit to Cuba began early in the morning at the Ministry of 
Foreign Relations. The visitors were met by Cuban Foreign 
Minister Roberto Robaina, who conversed with the visitors. 
President Manuel Hermoso Rojas thanked him for the hospitality 
shown during his visit and expressed a desire to meet with 
Robaina in the Canary Islands. Afterwards, Manuel Hermoso Rojas 
and Jose Ramon Fernandez signed a letter of intent which, among 
other items, includes the development of bilateral trade and the 
search, by Canarian authorities, for financing for financial 
projects in Cuba. In that area, next month, the Canarian 
Government will send a group of specialists to evaluate possible 
schemes of cooperation with Cuba. 
  In a news conference, President Hermoso Rojas referred to 
the 
possibility of cooperation between the governments of Cuba and 
Canary Islands: 
  [Begin recording] The Canary Islands is an enclave with very 
important ties with all of Europe. We believe that the Canary 
Islands can be an important platform of distribution to Latin 
America and Cuba of not only Canarian production but all 
products that could be received from Europe. The Canary Islands 
have industries that, because of the traditional characteristics 
of the Cuban and Canarian people, will allow for good contacts 
and business relations, especially in the 
agricultural-industrial sector. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

