<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Appoints Commission </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2302235794 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2212 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2302235794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 23 Feb (ACAN-EFE) -- The Central 
American Parliament (Parlacen) appointed today a mediation 
commission to help resolve the conflict between the government 
and its employees. The employees, who have been staging partial 
strikes for the past two weeks, requested Parlacen's mediation. 
  The Parlacen Information Office reported the commission 
members are: Guatemalan Deputies Vinicio Cerezo, Eduardo Meyer, 
and Manuel Conde and Marco Tulio Castillo, who is a Honduran and 
president of the [Parlacen] labor, union, and social issues 
commission. 
  Parlacen President Jose Francisco Guerrero, a Salvadoran, 
met 
with the government employees who had requested the mediation 
and offered to talk to Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon 
Carpio. 
  The request for Parlacen's mediation, which the executive 
still has not yet accepted, is another action taken by the 
strikers to pressure the government into accepting their demands 
for a 40-percent wage hike. 
  Approximately 30 leaders of the National Federation of State 
Workers Unions (Fenasteg), which represents approximately 
180,000 employees, remain in the government office waiting to 
meet with De Leon Carpio, who is not at the Presidential Palace. 
Fenasteg Secretary Armando Sanchez has said they will not 
abandon the palace or allow personnel to enter or leave the 
building until they get a positive response. 

</TEXT>

