<H3> <TI>   Aristide To Visit France, Meet With Mitterand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2302181894 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2302181894 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Exiled Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide will 
make a four-day private visit to France beginning 26 February. 
Notable activities during the visit will be meetings with French 
President Francois Mitterand and Foreign Affairs Minister Alain 
Juppe. This is what the Haitian Embassy in Paris said on the 
evening of 22 February. President Aristide will participate in 
an international colloquium for the fight [as heard] of Abbot 
Pierre, the founder the (Emaus) Charity Association organized 
under UNESCO. 
  Mr. Aristide, who was overthrown by a military coup d'etat 
in September 1991, rejected last week a plan, presented by 
Haitian parliamentarians, to unravel the current crisis. This 
plan, which is implicitly supported by UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali and which enjoys the support of Washington, 
provides notably for the appointment of a new prime minister, 
the early retirement of Army Commander in Chief General Raoul 
Cedras, and the installation of a new government of concord. 

</TEXT>

