<H3> <TI>   Aristide `Greatly Saddened' by Refugees' Ship Capsizing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2302221394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2302221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide said on 21 
February that he was greatly saddened by the murderous wreck of 
a boat carrying Haitian refugees off the Bahamas. Only three 
persons survived the 20 February wreck of a ship carrying 
between 20 and 40 Haitians, according to U.S. authorities. Five 
bodies, including those of a woman and four children, have been 
recovered. 
  In a communique, President Aristide, who is in exile in 
Washington, called on the international community once again to 
reinforce the sanctions against Haiti to compel the military to 
leave power. The sanctions are necessary and should have been 
applied a long time ago, the Haitian president wrote. Those who 
are supporting democracy in Haiti should show firmness, asserted 
President Aristide, adding that the authors of the coup d'etat 
must not be rewarded for barbarous actions. 

</TEXT>

