<F P=102>  FL2302190194 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2302190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Parliamentary Bloc of the National Front for 
Change and Democracy, BP-FNCD, is searching for unity. The 
principal leaders of the bloc who are currently in Washington, 
officially invited the members and political allies to join the 
party's leadership in its new position. In a letter addressed 
to the legislators in favor of the return of President Aristide, 
the bloc is inviting them to reunite, to close ranks in order to 
pursue together the struggle for democracy. This letter is 
addressed particularly to Senator Yvon Gislain and two FNCD 
deputies who approved a first plan for a solution to the crisis, 
siding with some legislators from the opposition. One FNCD 
ally, Deputy Samuel Madistin, who severely criticized the plan 
supported by the Americans and the United Nations also rose up 
against the initiative of the legislators without a mandate who 
are trying to involve the Legislative Branch as a whole. Deputy 
Madistin ascribes this plan to a vast international plot. 
[passage omitted] 

