<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Requests Information </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2402020794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2402020794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Colombian Foreign Ministry issued a communique 
tonight requesting official information from the United States 
on the services provided by Maria del Rosario Casas to the CIA 
in Mexico. The ministry is also requesting information on why 
Aldrich Ames, her husband, went to Colombia. In addition, the 
Foreign Ministry asked the prosecutor general and the attorney 
general to investigate Maria del Rosario Casas' conduct. 
  On this same issue, Noemi Sanin, Colombian foreign minister, 
has already offered the U.S. Government her full cooperation 
with the investigation into Maria del Rosario Casas' involvement 
in the case, the most talked-about spy case in recent times. 
Meanwhile, the Registrar's Office has disclosed the 
identification card of the accused. 
  The Foreign Ministry received orders today to maintain under 
strict reserve the curriculum vitae of Maria del Rosario Casas 
du Puy, Colombian Mata Hari captured by the FBI in the United 
States. She is accused of spying for Russia. This is Casas du 
Puy's photograph when she applied for a diplomatic post in 
Mexico. [video shows photograph of Maria del Rosario Casas] 
Here is what Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin has said: 
  [Begin Sanin recording] She is a well-known person from an 
established family. We hope, due to her background, she will be 
found innocent of the charges; if not, she must surrender to 
justice, because the accusations of the crime she has allegedly 
committed are very serious. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

