<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Urges `Immediate Cease-Fire' in Angola </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2302150694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1621 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2302150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 21 Feb (EFE) -- The Brazilian Government 
today lamented the "aggravation of the fratricidal war" in 
Angola, asking for an immediate cease-fire in the African 
country, which has strong cultural links with Brazil. 
  In an official note, the Brazilian Foreign Ministry stated 
that the cease-fire can contribute to the successful conclusion, 
in the short-term, of the negotiations under way in Lusaka, the 
capital of Zambia, between the Angolan Government and National 
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) guerrillas. 
  The note emphasizes that both sides should accept the result 
of the elections held in September 1992, in which Angolan 
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos emerged as the winner, and 
should observe the UN Security Council resolutions calling for a 
cease-fire. 
  The Brazilian Government stated that the aggravation of the 
Angolan war in the past few weeks "is more deplorable at a time 
in which there were sound hopes for peace on the basis of the 
conversations under way in Lusaka." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

